SIMPLE: juice
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Juice
<hw>Juice</hw> <pr>(j⟦umac⟧s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>juse</ets>, F. <ets>jus</ets> broth, gravy, juice, L.
<ets>jus</ets>; akin to Skr. <ets>y⟦umac⟧sha</ets>.]</ety> <def>The
characteristic fluid of any vegetable or animal substance; the sap or
part which can be expressed from fruit, etc.; the fluid part which
separates from meat in cooking.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An animal whose <qex>juices</qex> are unsound.</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>juice</qex> of July flowers.</q> <rj><qau>B.
Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>juice</qex> of Egypt's grape.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Letters which Edward Digby wrote in lemon <qex>juice</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cold water draws the <qex>juice</qex> of meat.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs.
Whitney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Juice</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Juice
<hw>Juice</hw> <pr>(j⟦umac⟧s)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To moisten; to
wet.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>juiced</ent>⟦br⟧
